To start a new process in C++ with one file descriptor connected to its input and output, you can use the `fork()` and `dup2()` functions. Here's a simple example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unistd.h> // for fork, execve, etc.
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <fcntl.h> // for open

int main() {
    int fd[2];
    pipe(fd); // create a pipe

    pid_t pid = fork();

    if (pid < 0) {
        std::cerr << "fork failed\n";
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) { // child process
        close(fd[1]); // close write end in child
        dup2(fd[0], STDIN_FILENO); // duplicate read end to stdin
        dup2(fd[0], STDOUT_FILENO); // duplicate read end to stdout
        close(fd[0]); // close the pipe file descriptor

        execlp("/bin/cat", "cat", nullptr); // replace child process with cat
    } else { // parent process
        close(fd[0]); // close read end in parent
        std::string message = "Hello, process!\n";
        write(fd[1], message.c_str(), message.size()); // write to the pipe
        close(fd[1]); // close write end in parent

        wait(nullptr); // wait for the child to finish

        std::cout << "Message sent to child process." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This example uses a pipe to connect the parent and child processes. The child process reads and writes to the pipe, while the parent sends a message to the child. The `cat` command is used as a simple example of a process that reads from stdin and outputs to stdout.
